******
[3] Peru (Piura): alert
Date: Sat 26 Mar 2016
Source: Diario Correo [in Spanish, trans. Corr.SB]
http://diariocorreo.pe/edicion/piura/piura-decretan-alerta-roja-por-brote-de-influenza-662420/


In the face of an outbreak of influenza A(H1N1) and influenza type B, the Piura Regional Health Directorate has declared a red alert in all health facilities, especially those located in the districts at risk. To date there have been 57 cases of influenza A(H1N1) in the region, of which 12 are confirmed and one person has died.

The extraordinary situation is contained in Resolution no. 150, signed by the Director of Health, Jesús Juárez Eyzaguirre, and is valid until [20 Jun 2016]. According to the resolution, the current situation shows an increase of confirmed cases of H1N1 influenza virus with high transmissibility for ecological, social, and environmental conditions caused by El Niño.

In this sense, health facilities should strengthen surveillance activities described in health directive no. 45 of the MoH referring to influenza or other respiratory viruses (OVR) and severe acute respiratory infections (SARI). They shall notify immediately and investigate clusters of cases of SARI or unusual cases. Similarly, outbreaks of acute respiratory infections in closed areas such as prisons, shelters, barracks, nursing homes, daycare centers, among other environments.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org

[A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Peru can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4124407,28228. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ

[The 1st 2 reports above refer to a recent surge in cases of influenza A(H1N1)pdm09 in Mexico and Kosovo, with high fatality rates in Mexico.

The 3rd report is from Peru. A health alert for both influenza A and B has been issued in Piura region, where to date, 12 cases of influenza A(H1N1) have been confirmed and one person has died. However the exact time period during which these cases and one death were reported is not mentioned.

It is imperative that triggers are established at regional, provincial, and national levels through routine surveillance of mild as well as severe disease, so that any extraordinary surge can be detected early, monitored, and responded to in a timely manner. - Mod.UBA]
